\subsection{Results about Embedding Subgroups}
If we have $H\subgroup G$, then there is an obvious inclusion $H\into G$
defined by sending $h\mapsto h$.


\begin{theorem}
If $H\subgroup G$, then $\id_{H}$ extends naturally to an embedding morphism
$H\into G$.
\end{theorem}

<<Theorem: if $H\subgroup G$, then $\id_{H}$ is an embedding morphism>>=
theorem Th11:
  for H being Subgroup of G
  ex f being Homomorphism of H,G
  st f = id (the carrier of H)
proof
  let H be Subgroup of G;
  set f = id (the carrier of H);
  A1: for h being Element of H holds f.h = h;
  f is Function of the carrier of H, the carrier of G
  proof
    B1: dom f = the carrier of H;
    rng f = the carrier of H;
    then rng f c= the carrier of G by GROUP_2:def 5;
    hence f is Function of the carrier of H, the carrier of G
    by B1, FUNCT_2:2;
  end;
  then reconsider f as Function of H, G;
  for g,h being Element of H
  holds f.(g * h) = (f.g) * (f.h)
  proof
    let g,h be Element of H;
    f.g = g & f.h = h by A1;
    then (f.g) * (f.h) = g*h by GROUP_2:43
                      .= f.(g * h) by A1;
    hence f.(g * h) = (f.g) * (f.h);
  end;

  then reconsider f as Homomorphism of H, G by GROUP_6:def 6;
  take f;
  thus f = id (the carrier of H);
end;
